
Optic neuritis
instance
Optic neuritis is inflammation of the optic nerve. It is also called papillitis (when the head of the optic nerve is involved) and retrobulbar neuritis (when the posterior of the nerve is involved). It is usually caused by other underlining diseases which must be treated first, many different conditions, and it may lead to complete or partial loss of vision in one or both eyes. Partial Vision loss which lasts a few minutes can be a indication of early onset MS , Diabe'tics, Low Phosphoris Levels or High K+ in Blood Levels Renal or Liver Toxicity (Late Stage) |} treatable Loss (ie. Blackness. The most common cause is multiple sclerosis which without treatment may lead to total loss of vision. Case Statistics
